00:07:27,919 --> 00:07:28,759
Fluency Builder.

128
00:07:29,699 --> 00:07:34,639
Okay, this first phrase is unusual because it actually happens at the end of sentences.

129
00:07:35,000 --> 00:07:39,220
This is very, very common with people who are making small talk or who are doing interviews.

130
00:07:39,920 --> 00:07:42,560
This is the phrase, is that right?

131
00:07:43,600 --> 00:07:46,240
So basically, you saw that in the first line, Mr.

132
00:07:46,319 --> 00:07:51,019
Parsons was talking to her and said, Well, I see you spent almost four years at the London Weekly.

133
00:07:51,240 --> 00:07:51,879
Is that right?

134
00:07:52,259 --> 00:07:55,540
So he's ending the sentence with this phrase.

135
00:07:55,540 --> 00:07:57,939
So he's making the sentence a question.

136
00:07:58,439 --> 00:07:59,980
I see that you did this.

137
00:08:00,259 --> 00:08:01,040
Is that right?

138
00:08:01,360 --> 00:08:08,060
So he's asking her to confirm the fact that he knows about her because maybe they've never really talked before.

139
00:08:08,819 --> 00:08:12,740
So this is a good way for him to ask her to give more details.

140
00:08:13,519 --> 00:08:13,779
Exactly.

141
00:08:14,199 --> 00:08:17,220
So, for example, Marco, I hear that you're from Ecuador.

142
00:08:17,259 --> 00:08:17,819
Is that right?

143
00:08:18,360 --> 00:08:18,879
That's right.

144
00:08:19,120 --> 00:08:25,120
So apart from ending the sentence like this, if maybe somebody asks you, is that right?

145
00:08:25,120 --> 00:08:26,339
You have to confirm.

146
00:08:26,480 --> 00:08:28,160
You have to say, Yes, that's right.

147
00:08:28,360 --> 00:08:29,279
Or, Yes.

148
00:08:29,920 --> 00:08:32,480
It's also good to elaborate, to give more details.

149
00:08:32,860 --> 00:08:34,120
So, Yes, I'm from Ecuador.

150
00:08:34,659 --> 00:08:37,100
I was born there, but I've lived in the United States.

151
00:08:37,279 --> 00:08:41,500
This is a way to give more information because that's basically what the person's asking.

152
00:08:41,700 --> 00:08:47,000
Yeah, I think it wouldn't be very good if you're at a job interview and the person says, Is that right?

153
00:08:47,000 --> 00:08:48,139
And you say, Yes, that's right.

154
00:08:48,379 --> 00:08:49,779
And then you don't say anything else.

155
00:08:49,779 --> 00:08:54,659
So, yeah, basically the point is you have to confirm or deny.

156
00:08:54,799 --> 00:08:55,740
You have to say, Yes, that's right.

157
00:08:55,740 --> 00:08:56,700
Or, No, that's not right.

158
00:08:56,740 --> 00:08:59,019
And then you have to give some information about the question.

159
00:09:00,419 --> 00:09:00,799
All right.

160
00:09:01,059 --> 00:09:02,100
Now, moving on.

161
00:09:02,179 --> 00:09:11,179
When Rebecca, again, was talking about her job, she was saying, It's tough and I didn't have many responsibilities and I found it quite frustrating.

162
00:09:11,679 --> 00:09:11,879
Okay.

163
00:09:11,879 --> 00:09:13,500
So this is like lost and found.

164
00:09:13,500 --> 00:09:15,559
Like I lost my hat and I found it later.

165
00:09:16,159 --> 00:09:16,679
No, no.

166
00:09:16,679 --> 00:09:19,580
This is what's interesting about this verb find.

167
00:09:19,840 --> 00:09:25,299
We are not actually looking for something or we didn't actually find something we were looking for.

168
00:09:25,700 --> 00:09:27,899
This is kind of a realization, right?

169
00:09:28,340 --> 00:09:28,580
That's right.

170
00:09:28,600 --> 00:09:29,960
It's like a feeling.

171
00:09:30,779 --> 00:09:33,320
So I find this movie boring.

172
00:09:33,700 --> 00:09:35,860
That means I think this movie is boring.

173
00:09:36,620 --> 00:09:38,639
It's the way that you're thinking about something.

174
00:09:38,879 --> 00:09:39,200
That's right.

175
00:09:39,200 --> 00:09:42,899
Or you can say, Oh, I found Paris to be quite an expensive city.

176
00:09:43,559 --> 00:09:44,460
Yeah, pretty expensive.

177
00:09:44,460 --> 00:09:46,580
So this is your impression.

178
00:09:46,799 --> 00:09:48,799
This is the way that you feel about something.

179
00:09:49,840 --> 00:09:53,159
So this is another way that you can use this word to find.

180
00:09:53,940 --> 00:10:04,279
Now, again, when Rebecca talked about proving herself, she used a very interesting, I would say phrase, a very popular, well-known phrase, Slowly but surely.

181
00:10:05,440 --> 00:10:05,559
Okay.

182
00:10:05,840 --> 00:10:09,240
So slowly but surely is the opposite of right away.

183
00:10:10,059 --> 00:10:10,120
Right.

184
00:10:10,379 --> 00:10:13,399
So something that happens right away is immediate.

185
00:10:13,399 --> 00:10:15,200
Like I got promoted right away.

186
00:10:16,279 --> 00:10:24,440
But slowly but surely means after lots of time and even hard work, this good thing happened or it's usually a good thing actually.

187
00:10:25,080 --> 00:10:25,240
Yeah.

188
00:10:25,360 --> 00:10:31,720
It's you're basically saying that you didn't do anything very quickly, but you did it very well.

189
00:10:31,960 --> 00:10:36,620
So slowly but surely I finished building my home.

190
00:10:37,200 --> 00:10:37,240
Right.

191
00:10:37,360 --> 00:10:40,440
So it didn't happen overnight, but it did happen over time.

192
00:10:40,440 --> 00:10:42,720
You can also say this about studying a language.

193
00:10:43,860 --> 00:10:48,519
You know, at the beginning, learning English was really hard, but slowly but surely I became fluent.

194
00:10:49,340 --> 00:10:49,519
Exactly.

195
00:10:49,820 --> 00:10:50,039
Okay.

196
00:10:50,299 --> 00:10:52,179
So slowly but surely.

197
00:10:52,740 --> 00:11:03,440
And the last phrase that we have for you today, you may have seen that Rebecca used this phrase to be honest a couple of times before explaining something.

198
00:11:03,740 --> 00:11:05,820
So why does she say to be honest?

199
00:11:05,820 --> 00:11:11,460
To be honest is sometimes something we say in English to fill some space or some time.

200
00:11:12,000 --> 00:11:12,720
We call it filler.

201
00:11:13,179 --> 00:11:15,399
But it's also a way to introduce something that's negative.

202
00:11:16,000 --> 00:11:20,539
So for example, in this dialogue, she's talking about her negative experiences.

203
00:11:21,000 --> 00:11:22,240
You know, my job was tough.

204
00:11:22,379 --> 00:11:23,460
My experience was bad.

205
00:11:23,799 --> 00:11:28,460
So she says, to be honest, it wasn't the best experience, but I learned from it.

206
00:11:28,620 --> 00:11:32,440
She's saying this to introduce some things that are maybe not positive, not happy things.

207
00:11:32,740 --> 00:11:33,000
That's right.

208
00:11:33,000 --> 00:11:36,559
So it's another way of saying, look, I'm going to tell you the truth.

209
00:11:37,139 --> 00:11:40,659
It may not be something positive, but you know, this is what happened.

210
00:11:40,919 --> 00:11:45,899
So to be honest, I didn't really like my last employer or something like that.

211
00:11:46,059 --> 00:11:47,460
Well, you can even talk about this with your friends.

212
00:11:47,899 --> 00:11:50,399
So, hey, Marco, did you like that movie Shutter Island?

213
00:11:50,860 --> 00:11:53,220
To be honest, I didn't really see it.

214
00:11:53,500 --> 00:11:53,519
Oh.

215
00:11:53,980 --> 00:11:54,200
I fell asleep.

216
00:11:55,279 --> 00:11:57,200
Or you could say, to be honest, I didn't love it.

217
00:11:57,340 --> 00:11:58,419
I didn't really like it.

218
00:11:58,860 --> 00:11:59,200
Exactly.

219
00:11:59,200 --> 00:11:59,379
Exactly.

220
00:11:59,740 --> 00:12:04,259
So it's a very good phrase, but don't overuse it.

221
00:12:04,360 --> 00:12:08,379
I think sometimes you get into the habit of using it all the time.

222
00:12:08,820 --> 00:12:16,120
And just like like, you know, well, you know, like I went to the movies like yesterday, like to be honest.

223
00:12:16,899 --> 00:12:21,240
So try to keep these fillers, as you described them, to a minimum.

224
00:12:21,240 --> 00:12:22,980
So don't really use them too much.

225
00:12:23,220 --> 00:12:23,299
Yes.

226
00:12:23,539 --> 00:12:31,720
Say thoughts and ideas, nice action verbs, not too much fillers, because sometimes, especially in an interview, it makes people think that you don't really know much to say.

227
00:12:32,120 --> 00:12:32,580
Yeah, exactly.

